Great question — this is a classic gotcha when moving from ASP.NET Core to MAUI.

**In ASP.NET Core**, a new DI scope is created automatically **per HTTP request**, so `AddScoped<MyDbContext>()` gives you a fresh instance each request.

**In MAUI, there is no per-request scope.** The app has a single root scope for its entire lifetime. This means `AddScoped` behaves essentially like `AddSingleton` — you get **one DbContext instance for the whole app**, so tracked entities, cached data, and change-tracker state all persist across navigations.

### Fixes

1. **Use `AddTransient<MyDbContext>()`** — gives a new instance every time it's injected. Simple, but you lose shared-context-per-unit-of-work.

2. **Use `IServiceScopeFactory` to create manual scopes** (closest to the ASP.NET Core model):

   ```csharp
   public class MyViewModel
   {
       private readonly IServiceScopeFactory _scopeFactory;

       public MyViewModel(IServiceScopeFactory scopeFactory)
           => _scopeFactory = scopeFactory;

       public async Task LoadDataAsync()
       {
           using var scope = _scopeFactory.CreateScope();
           var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();
           // db is fresh; disposed at end of this block
       }
   }
   ```

3. **Use a DbContext factory** (EF Core's built-in pattern):

   ```csharp
   // Registration
   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>(opts =>
       opts.UseSqlite("..."));

   // Usage
   public class MyViewModel(IDbContextFactory<MyDbContext> factory)
   {
       public async Task LoadDataAsync()
       {
           using var db = factory.CreateDbContext();
           // fresh context every time
       }
   }
   ```

Option 3 (`AddDbContextFactory`) is generally the **recommended approach** for MAUI/Blazor/desktop apps since it was designed exactly for this scenario.
